**Summary of the Bill – Section-by-Section Breakdown**

**Sec. 70501** – **Termination of Previously-Owned Clean Vehicle Credit**  
Amends Section 25E(g) to cut off the $7,500 clean-vehicle credit for previously-owned EVs after September 30, 2025, instead of the previous December 31, 2032 deadline. The change applies to any qualifying used EV purchased after that date.

**Sec. 70502** – **Termination of Clean Vehicle Credit**  
Repeals the $7,500 new-EV credit for vehicles placed in service after September 30, 2025. It also removes the 30D(e) sub-paragraphs that allowed bonus credits for critical-mineral content and union labor, streamlining the credit to a simple phase-out.

**Sec. 70503** – **Termination of Qualified Commercial Clean Vehicles Credit**  
Ends the Section 45W credit for commercial EVs after September 30, 2025, instead of December 31, 2032. The credit, worth up to $7,500 per vehicle, is eliminated for new commercial clean-vehicle purchases after that cutoff.

**Sec. 70504** – **Termination of Alternative Fuel Vehicle Refueling Property Credit**  
Closes the Section 30C credit for EV-charging stations and alternative-fuel infrastructure after June 30, 2026, instead of December 31, 2032. The credit, capped at $100,000 per station, is phased out for property placed in service after that date.

**Sec. 70505** – **Termination of Energy Efficient Home Improvement Credit**  
Axs the Section 25C credit for energy-efficient home upgrades after December 31, 2025. The credit, worth up to $1,200 annually, is limited to improvements placed in service by that date.

**Sec. 70506** – **Termination of Residential Clean Energy Credit**  
Ends the Section 25D credit for residential solar, wind, and battery storage after December 31, 2025. The credit, worth up to 30 % of installation costs, is cut off for systems placed in service after that date.

**Sec. 70507** – **Termination of Energy Efficient Commercial Buildings Deduction**  
Repeals the Section 179D deduction for energy-efficient commercial buildings after June 30, 2026. The deduction, worth up to $5 per square foot, is eliminated for construction beginning after that cutoff.

**Sec. 70508** – **Termination of New Energy Efficient Home Credit**  
Ends the Section 45L credit for energy-efficient new homes after June 30, 2026. The credit, worth up to $2,500 per dwelling unit, is phased out for homes the construction of which begins after that date.

**Sec. 70509** – **Termination of Cost Recovery for Energy Property**  
Repeals the Section 168(e)(3)(B)(vi) accelerated depreciation bonus for energy property placed in service after December 31, 2024. The 30 % bonus is rescinded for property the construction of which begins after that date.

**Sec. 70510** – **Modifications of Zero-Emission Nuclear Power Production Credit**  
Bars any Section 45U nuclear-production credit for taxpayers that are “specified foreign entities” or “foreign-influenced entities” as defined in Section 7701(a)(51)(B) and (D). The ban takes effect for taxable years beginning after the date of enactment.

**Sec. 70511** – **Termination of Clean Hydrogen Production Credit**  
Moves the deadline for the Section 45V clean-hydrogen credit from January 1, 2033, to January 1, 2028. The credit is phased out for production beginning after that earlier date.

**Sec. 70512** – **Termination and Restrictions on Clean Electricity Production Credit**  
Kills the Section 45Y clean-electricity production credit for wind and solar facilities placed in service after December 31, 2027. It also bars any credit for facilities that begin construction after December 31, 2025, if they receive “material assistance” from a “prohibited foreign entity.”

**Sec. 70513** – **Termination and Restrictions on Clean Electricity Investment Credit**  
Repeals the Section 48E clean-electricity investment credit for wind and solar property placed in service after December 31, 2027. It also imposes a 100 % recapture tax on any “applicable payment” to a “specified taxpayer” that later receives a prohibited-foreign-entity credit.

**Sec. 70514** – **Phase-Out and Restrictions on Advanced Manufacturing Production Credit**  
Caps the Section 45X advanced-manufacturing credit for critical minerals at 75 % in 2031, 50 % in 2032, 25 % in 2033, and 0 % thereafter. It also bars the credit for wind-energy components produced after December 31, 2027, and for metallurgical coal produced after December 31, 2029.

**Sec. 70515** – **Restriction on the Extension of Advanced Energy Project Credit Program**  
Prevents any future increases in the Section 48C advanced-energy project credit cap. The existing $2 billion annual cap remains fixed.

**Sec. 70521** – **Extension and Modification of Clean Fuel Production Credit**  
Mandates that clean-burning fuel qualify for the Section 45Z credit only if its feedstock is grown or produced in the U.S., Mexico, or Canada. It also bans negative emissions rates and extends the credit’s expiration to December 31, 2029.

**Sec. 70522** – **Restrictions on Carbon Oxide Sequestration Credit**  
Bars the Section 45Q carbon-sequestration credit for taxpayers that are “specified foreign entities” or “foreign-influenced entities.” The credit is also restructured to allow only secure geological storage, not reuse as a tertiary injectant.

**Sec. 70523** – **Intangible Drilling and Development Costs Taken into Account for Purposes of Computing Adjusted Financial Statement Income**  
Requires taxpayers to subtract both depreciation and depletion deductions when reconciling book income to taxable income for intangible drilling costs. The rule applies to taxable years beginning after December 31, 2025.

**Sec. 70524** – **Income from Hydrogen Storage, Carbon Capture, Advanced Nuclear, Hydropower, and Geothermal Energy Added to Qualifying Income of Certain Publicly Traded Partnerships**  
Expands the list of income types that qualify for the Section 7704(d) publicly-traded partnership “carried-interest” exemption to include hydrogen storage, carbon capture, advanced-nuclear generation, hydropower, and geothermal energy.

**Sec. 70525** – **Allow for Payments to Certain Individuals Who Dye Fuel**  
Creates a new refundable tax credit under Section 6435 that pays dye-plant operators the excise tax they already paid on dyed diesel or kerosene that is later used as untaxed fuel. The credit is available for fuel removed on or after 180 days after enactment.

**Sec. 70531** – **Modifications to De Minimis Entry Privilege for Commercial Shipments**  
Imposes a civil penalty of up to $5,000 for the first violation and $10,000 for each subsequent violation on any person who abuses the Section 321 de-minimis customs exemption. The penalty takes effect 30 days after enactment, and the de-minimis exception itself sunsets on July 1, 2027.

**Sec. 70601** – **Modification and Extension of Limitation on Excess Business Losses of Noncorporate Taxpayers**  
Makes the Section 461(l) excess-business-loss limitation permanent, removing the 2029 sunset. It also lowers the threshold amounts for 2025 and 2024, making the cap apply to more taxpayers.

**Sec. 70602** – **Treatment of Payments from Partnerships to Partners for Property or Services**  
Revises Section 707(a)(2) to eliminate the “under regulations” language, giving the IRS authority to issue narrower rules on when partnership-to-partner payments are treated as guaranteed payments versus distributive shares.

**Sec. 70603** – **Excessive Employee Remuneration from Controlled Group Members and Allocation of Deduction**  
Expands Section 162(m)’s $1 million cap on deductible executive pay to include remuneration paid by any member of a controlled group to a “specified covered employee” of the group. The cap is allocated among group members based on their share of total covered-compensation.

**Sec. 70604** – **Excise Tax on Certain Remittance Transfers**  
Imposes a 1 % excise tax on remittance transfers funded with cash, money orders, or similar instruments. The tax is collected by the remittance-transfer provider and remitted quarterly to the Treasury.

**Sec. 70605** – **Enforcement Provisions with Respect to COVID-Related Employee Retention Credits**  
Imposes a $1,000 per-document penalty on “COVID-ERTC promoters” who fail to meet due-diligence requirements when preparing claims. It also bars any ERTC refund or credit for claims not filed by January 31, 2024, and extends the assessment period for ERTC-related deficiencies to six years.

**Sec. 70606** – **Social Security Number Requirement for American Opportunity and Lifetime Learning Credits**  
Mandates that taxpayers include the student’s Social Security number (and the institution’s employer identification number) on the return in order to claim either the American Opportunity or Lifetime Learning credit.

**Sec. 70607** – **Task Force on the Replacement of Direct File**  
Appropriates $15 million to fund a Treasury task force that must deliver a report within 90 days of enactment assessing the cost, feasibility, and taxpayer preferences for a government-run or publicly partnered free-file tax system. [end of text]


